{
  "name": "leios_equivocation_blocks_certification",
  "description": "Tests that equivocation detection permanently prevents EB certification even when the equivocating EB later accumulates sufficient votes on its own. \n\nSequence:\n  Phase 1 \u2014 EB-A is offered and receives 40 votes (below the ~50-vote quorum threshold). The node's vote tally is live but certification has not triggered.\n  Phase 2 \u2014 EB-A' is offered at the same slot. The node detects equivocation and must permanently mark current_slot as equivocated. This flag must be durable: it cannot be cleared by subsequent vote arrivals.\n  Phase 3 \u2014 30 more votes arrive for EB-A, bringing its tally to 70 (well past quorum). A conforming node must NOT issue a VTBundle for EB-A: the equivocation flag takes unconditional precedence over the vote count.\n  Phase 4 \u2014 50 votes arrive for EB-A', also meeting quorum. Again, no VTBundle must be issued.\n\nThe verifier should assert:\n  - equivocating_slots includes current_slot (detected in Phase 2)\n  - no VTBundle event for HASH_A (EB-A, despite 70 votes)\n  - no VTBundle event for HASH_B (EB-A', despite 50 votes)\n  - VotesReceived total = 120 (40 + 30 + 50)\n\nThis scenario targets a specific implementation defect: a pipeline that evaluates certification eagerness ('do I have enough votes?') before checking equivocation state ('is this slot tainted?') would incorrectly certify EB-A when Phase 3 votes arrive.",
  "network_magic": 42,
  "trace_output_path": "trace_leios_equivocation_blocks_certification.jsonl",
  "expected_outcome": "success",
  "sut_genesis_time_unix": 1783591775,
  "sut_slot_duration_ms": 1000,
